Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9. Boil a half-full #kettle{}.

Chop the @Sweet Potato{2} into 1cm chunks (no need to peel).

Put the sweet potato chunks onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer. TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary. When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{16-18%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, pour the boiled water into a #medium saucepan{} with @salt{1/4%tsp} on high heat. Add the @Jasmine Rice{150%g} and cook for ~{12-13%minutes}.

Drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pan. Cover with a #lid{} and leave to the side until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, zest and cut the @Lime{1} into wedges.

Peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Drain and rinse the @Lentils{1%carton} in a sieve.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @Red Thai Style Paste{50%g}, @Thai Style Spice Mix{1%sachet} (add less if you'd prefer things milder) and garlic. Stir-fry until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add the @Coconut Milk{180%ml}, @Soy Sauce{15%ml}, @Peanut Butter{30%g} and lentils to the pan. Stir well until combined.

Bring to the boil and simmer until thickened, ~{6-8%minutes}. TIP: If your peanut butter has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for ~{1%minute}.

Once ready, stir the roasted sweet potato, @Sweet Chilli Sauce{32%g} and a squeeze of lime juice into the lentils. Remove from the heat.

Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed. Add a splash of water if it's a little thick.

When everything's ready, fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and stir through the lime zest.

Share the zesty rice between your bowls. Top with the lentil curry.

Serve any remaining lime wedges alongside for squeezing over. Enjoy!